<div id="review_2226956178" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2226956178" />
    <a title="Ned Hanlon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21847297-ned-hanlon"><img alt="Ned Hanlon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483734385p2/21847297.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2226956178?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ned Hanlon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ned Hanlon" href="/user/show/21847297-ned-hanlon">Ned Hanlon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140455137" href="/book/show/4480555-islam-and-the-crusades">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2226956178" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10721492946343452866">Really neat but kind of meandering (which might be the point). The author tells about his life through an endless number of anecdotes and pearls of wisdom, skipping from place to place and time to time with only vague themes or similarities to link them. It is life as a collection of footnotes, not as a cohesive novel. Most of it is startlingly prosaic but there are a few moments of beautiful poetry (especially when bemoans the lot of a lifelong soldier subjected to the ravages of old age).<br/><br/>Desti</span>
  <span id="freeText10721492946343452866" style="display:none">Really neat but kind of meandering (which might be the point). The author tells about his life through an endless number of anecdotes and pearls of wisdom, skipping from place to place and time to time with only vague themes or similarities to link them. It is life as a collection of footnotes, not as a cohesive novel. Most of it is startlingly prosaic but there are a few moments of beautiful poetry (especially when bemoans the lot of a lifelong soldier subjected to the ravages of old age).<br /><br />Destiny had forsaken me, leaving me like<br />An exhausted pack-camel abandoned in the wastes.<br />My eighty years have sapped all my strength<br />So that when I try to stand, I am broken.<br />I perform my prayers seated, for bowing<br />If I tried it, would be, for me, impossible.<br />This condition has warned me<br />That a journey is coming, and its time is nigh.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10721492946343452866" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


