  <span id="freeText13848952984068176107" style="display:none">Slightly repetitive in his description of warfare and hunting, ibn Munqidh was nonetheless an interesting character with a life of great interest to those wanting to read about the day-to-day life of the period. Interesting observations and anecdotes make the book worth reading overall. <br /><br />Of particular interest are a Christian attempting to 'clean' a tent infested with fleas using fire, with predictable results (p. 99); a man releasing a newly captured leopard at a drinking party, with predictable results (p. 124) and a demented old woman attempting to clean the smell of cheese out of a headscarf, only for her son to point out that she was not using a piece of soap but rather a piece of cheese, hence the cheese smell (p. 199).<br /><br /><i>A man's soul will always shudder at such dangers and loathe them. But once a man of courage enters the fray of battle and wades among its throngs, all that shaking, shuddering and changing of colour disappears.</i> (p. 98)</span>
